od carbon dioxide levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eamygdala and hypothalamus project to respiratory centres\u003C/strong\u003E in the brainstem, allowing emotional states to influence breathing patterns. This explains why fear, anxiety, and other emotional states can alter respiratory rate and depth independently of metabolic demands.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulates the phrenic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The limbic system influences breathing via brainstem centres rather than direct nerve stimulation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitors blood carbon dioxide levels\u003C/strong\u003E - Chemoreceptors, not the limbic system, monitor blood gases\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls bronchial smooth muscle only\u003C/strong\u003E - The limbic system primarily influences respiratory rate and depth rather than airway tone\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulates surfactant production\u003C/strong\u003E - Surfactant production is controlled by local factors in the lungs, not the limbic system\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis limbic control allows for behavioural adaptation of breathing patterns during emotional responses, preparing the body for potential fight-or-flight responses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The limbic system influences respiratory rate and depth via connections between the amygdala and hypothalamus to brainstem respiratory centres.","Emotional states like fear and anxiety can increase ventilation through limbic system activation.","The limbic system provides behavioural and emotional modulation of breathing independent of metabolic control."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, 